Am I the only person who hasn't heard of "cooler corn"?
As an obsessive food nerd, you'd expect that I would have at least heard of it, but over the weekend I was blind-sided by the simple genius of this method for cooking loads of corn on the cob perfectly.
I was hepped to it while visiting my family. Short story: We like corn on the cob. And with eight adults at the table, that means a couple of dozen ears. We would have used the lobster pot to cook them all, but the crab pot was busy steaming crabs. "Let's do cooler corn!" Before I can ask "what the hell is cooler corn?" a Coleman cooler appears from the garage, is wiped clean, then filled with the shucked ears. Next, two kettles-full of boiling water are poured over the corn and the top closed.
Then nothing. When we sat down to dinner 30 minutes later and opened it, the corn was perfectly cooked. My mind was blown. And I'm told that the corn will remain at the perfect level of doneness for a couple of hours.
Turns out, Cooler Corn is pretty well known among the outdoorsy set But for those of us who avoid tents as much as possible, it's perfect for large barbecues and way less of mess than grilling. In fact, I may even buy another cooler just so I'm ready for this summer. Now that I'm in the know.

Also, as I have always done- be sure to add some OLD BAY¬Æ Seasoning ! üòâüá∫üá∏üá∫üá∏üá∫üá∏üá∫üá∏

Just know I love and appreciate you....

text: It'll be three years on Dec. 11th, since I was released. I was just a 21 year old kid who loved to live. I went in for a charge that I still don't feel was deserving. Picked up more time because I had a huge chip on my shoulder... Long story short, I lost a part of me in there. And just when I was finally beginning to get settled in, and find a new me, they kicked me out. I was forced to leave several good people behind. It was the only people I had close for 13 and a half years. Now I'm starting all over again... I know there are bad people out there. I was locked up with the worst. Seven years living between Death Row inmates... Was within two cells of three different suicide victims... Point is this,.. Never take for granted what you have in life. No matter how good you think you're living, it can all be taken from you in an instant. Keep your hands on the steering wheel. Because life is full of curves...

text: I lost 13 and a half years in prison because I was lost and trying to find myself. I lost so much more along the way. I always questioned how I could cry over a movie's ending, yet never shed a tear at a funeral. How could anyone retire a police officer, and a prison guard, yet still cry when you see someone else smile? I wasted so many years trying to fit in with everyone else, when most of the others weren't who they really seemed to be... I'm posting this as a Man. Hoping to reach out to other men. Or anyone that can find strength or reasoning in it... We don't have to live up to reputations, qualifications, or expectations. Just find your own path. Your own happiness. I chose not to be a salmon always swimming against the current of life. Or a catfish waiting on something good to come along. I'm chose my own speed and path. Maybe like when fish first grew legs and learned to walk on land... I challenge anyone that takes the time to read this, to post their own story, path, or plans. If you tag me, I will respond... We aren't nearly as different as what we try to be... Love all

text:
I have too much to say, and not enough patience to put it on paper... I am so tired of all the black/white/brown/yellow/purple bullshit. The one thing that holds humanity back more than anything else, is pride... As humans we seek out differences. We try to find ways to make us better than the person next to us. We build borders and boundaries. We have isolated neighborhoods and Indian reservations. We waste so much time trying to be different, when all we need to do is find a way to be OUR best. Doesn't matter what the person next to you is doing, as long as YOU are doing YOUR best.. What in the hell happened to us? Why are we so satisfied with this path? Why are we so content with just being another number? I am not. I will NOT follow this path. Our ancestors from every race and culture, dedicated all they had to get us to where we are today. Yet here we are today more worried about what's on Facebook, than what we did to help ourselves or someone else. I'm no better than anyone else. I am guilty of the same human flaws. But I WILL acknowledge and make the necessary changes in orders to provide a healthy, beneficial influence on our growth. As a whole. Not as an individual... if you aren't helping humanity grow and prosper, then you are just holding the rest of us back...

Respectfully Hopeful. Just another drunken rant...

text: I read so many different types of comments on facebook, from so many different types of people. My friends come in all colors, shapes and religions. One thing that I've noticed tho, is this one common characteristic trait... We are all, on different levels, really decent people. Good parents, good friends, good Americans... It breaks my heart to see so many different types of people, from completely different types of life, fighting and arguing about bullshit, when we actually have so much in common. We are not all the same. We are not all common. We are individuals. And it just so happens that we have quite a bit in common with a hell of a lot of people that you might never have expected... Forget everything you think you know, everything you have been taught... For once, let's make this era about change. Let's open our hearts, and our eyes, enough to recognize the similarities, while forgetting about the differences. Let's be leaders. Let's truly preach, teach, and practice love... Together, we truly can make a difference... Thank you... One love
